ons \n�  Breaking down complex goals \n�  Making independent, autonomous decisions \n�  Learning and adapting dynamically \n�  Taking initiative without constant human supervision\n02\nAGENTIC AI FOR EXECUTIVES\n1.1 The Terminology Maze \nWe live in an era where the term "AI" is liberally sprinkled across marketing materials, \nproduct descriptions, and tech conversations. Everything seems to be labeled as AI, \ncreating a fog of technological hype that obscures genuine innovation. This \nwidespread labeling has led to significant confusion, particularly between traditional \nAI, non-agentic AI, and the emerging world of agentic systems.  \nThere are actually different types of AI, each with its own capabilities. When you take\n\nComputational \nresources\nEthical\nFramework\nSkill\nProficiency\nIndustry\nspecific\nreadiness\nData\nQuality\nmeets \nthreshold?\nData Quality \nImprovement\nAdequateInadequate Yes\nTeam formation\nUnestablished\nEstablished\nTalent \nacquisition\nstrategy\nImplement Cont monitoring\nM H F R C\nInsuffient\nSkill Gap Suffiecient \nTalent\nNo\nTraining\nUpskilling\nIntra Upgrade\nCloud Setup\nTalent\nAssessment\nCompliance Gov\nFramework\nDevelop AI Ethics\nData Standardization\nM - Manufacturing  H - Healthcare  F - Financial Services  R - Retail  C - Construction\nAdequate\nResource\nAugmentation\nPlan\nInadequate\n43\nAGENTIC AI FOR EXECUTIVES\nB. Industry-Wise Readiness  \nBefore an organization moves forward with implementing Agentic AI, it is crucial to \nassess its readiness across several key areas. These evaluation parameters serve as \na checklist, helping organizations ensure they have the right foundational elements in \nplace before proceeding with agentic AI adoption. By evaluating each of these\n\nlegacy systems. \nOur solution ensures reliability, even as environments evolve or errors arise, and is \ndeployable in private clouds while maintaining enterprise compliance. Backed by a \nteam of world-class engineers, Emergence 